Purpose

This document establishes consistent development rules and practices for all AI-assisted coding within the Keeper Platform. Cursor will adhere to these rules to ensure clarity, maintainability, and architectural fidelity. All folder-level README files will act as living micro-specs and must be updated automatically by Cursor during development.

⚙️ Cursor Rules

1. Tech Stack Awareness

Cursor must conform to the platform's defined stack:

Frontend: React + TypeScript + TailwindCSS + Shadcn + Framer Motion

Backend: Express.js + Prisma + Zod + Railway PostgreSQL

Infrastructure: Vercel (Blob, Hosting), Railway (DB)

Use pnpm for all package management: Never mix with npm or yarn

Use npx only for one-time CLI utilities like prisma or tailwindcss init

2. File & Folder Conventions

/components/FeatureName/ with index.tsx, types.ts, colocated subcomponents

Use .ts for type/config-only files; .tsx only for files with JSX

Route handlers go in /api/feature/route.ts

Place all schemas next to their route or usage

3. Theme Assignment

All users must be assigned the Keeper Classic theme by default upon signup.

Theme is stored in the UserSettings model (relation to Theme via preferred_theme_id)

4. Strict Type Discipline

All functions and components must have explicit types.

Zod validation must accompany all user input and API request bodies.

Do not use any. Use unknown + narrowing when required.

5. Dynamic Theming

Dynamic theming must be initialized through user settings.

Theme tokens come from database-linked Theme model.

Do not hardcode colors. Use Tailwind and/or CSS variables based on theme structure.

6. Authentication

Use kam (Keeper Auth Module) structure to scaffold all auth routes and logic.


Cursor must never expose or hardcode secrets.

7. Reference ...\prisma\MODEL_REFERENCE.MD for an index of data models and relationships

8. 📦 Use `pnpm` exclusively for all package installations and dependency management.

❌ Do not use `npm install` or `yarn add`. This breaks lockfile integrity and may corrupt the build environment.

✅ When adding new packages, always run: `pnpm add <package>`

📂 This project uses `pnpm-lock.yaml` as the source of truth for dependencies.

💡 If you're unsure, refer to the `preinstall` script in `package.json` which enforces this policy.
